Virtual threads, Java twenty-one's big shift.

Until Java twenty-one, every thread in Java was what we now call a platform thread, which is just a thin wrapper around an operating-system thread. And operating-system threads are expensive. Each one costs around a megabyte of stack memory, carries kernel scheduling overhead, and in practice you can only have on the order of ten thousand of them in flight before a real machine starts to struggle. That ceiling shaped a decade of Java concurrency.

Virtual threads are a completely different, virtual-machine-managed alternative. They are lightweight, measured in kilobytes rather than megabytes, and the virtual machine multiplexes many of them onto a small pool of real platform threads, which it calls carriers. The magic is in blocking. When a virtual thread blocks on input or output, the virtual machine simply parks it and lets its carrier pick up a different virtual thread. The expensive operating-system thread is never actually sitting idle.

The practical effect is enormous. You can have millions of concurrent virtual threads all waiting on the network at once. Code that used to require a complex non-blocking framework, with async callbacks and reactive plumbing, can now be written as plain, blocking, one-thread-per-request code, and it still scales. The modern shape is one virtual thread per task, using the virtual-thread-per-task executor, with no pool sizing to tune.

Two pieces of guidance. Use virtual threads for input-output-bound work, like an HTTP server or database calls; that is the entire reason they exist. Use platform threads for see-pee-you-bound work, because a virtual thread that never blocks just pins its carrier and gains you nothing. And one sharp warning: do not use synchronized on the hot path of virtual-thread code, because synchronized pins the virtual thread to its carrier and defeats the whole model. Reach for reentrant lock instead, which we will meet shortly.
